  "prompt": "What are stars made out of?",
  "response": "Stars are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium, which are the two lightest and most abundant elements in the universe. The process of nuclear fusion occurring in their cores transforms hydrogen into helium, releasing immense amounts of energy in the form of light and heat. \n\nIn addition to hydrogen and helium, stars can also contain trace amounts of heavier elements, often referred to as \"metals\" in astronomical terms. These can include elements like carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, and various others, which are produced in the later stages of stellar evolution or during supernova explosions.\n\nThe exact composition of a star can vary depending on its size, age, and stage in its life cycle. For example, more massive stars may form heavier elements through fusion processes as they age, while stars like our Sun primarily fuse hydrogen into helium throughout most of their lives.",
